rtheless suggests the existence of traditions comparable to those found in Scandinavia and Germany. Tree symbolismhelped early English Christians to understand how the beliefs of their ancestors about trees, posts, and pillars paralleled the appearance of similar objects in the Old Testament. In this way, the religious symbols of their forebears were aligned with precursors to the cross in Scripture. Literary evidence from England and Scandinavia similarly indicates a shared tradition of associations between the bodies of humans, trees, and other plant-life. Though potentially ancient, these ideas flourished amongst the abundance of vegetative symbolism found in the Christian tradition. Michael Bintley is Senior Lecturer in Medieval Literature at Canterbury Christ Church University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aTreesxHistoryyTo 1500zEngland. 0aTreesxReligious aspectszEngland. 0aTreeszEnglandxReligious aspects. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Saxon Material Culture.  aAnglo-Saxon Religion.  aCanterbury Christ Church University.  aChristian.  aEngland.  aMichael Bintley.  aPagan.  aScripture.  aTrees.1 aBintley, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782044345?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782044345423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782044345/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles